    "brief": "**Sustainment Estimate Brief \u2014 DTG 272025Z APR 2026**\n\n## PARA 1 \u2014 SITUATION\nSupported force is a **MEU(SOC)** of **2,200** personnel operating over **30 days** in **tropical** conditions at **high** opscale, with planning basis **expeditionary_austere**. Sustainment demand reflects elevated fuel, ammunition, medical, and repair-part consumption associated with distributed expeditionary operations and limited local support infrastructure.\n\n## PARA 2 \u2014 MISSION\nLOGCOM sustainment cell estimates, sources, and positions Classes I-IX support required to sustain the force through the 30-day operational window. Priority is to maintain continuity of supply to forward elements while mitigating shortfalls in high-variance classes through phased pre-positioning and contingency sourcing.\n\n## PARA 3 \u2014 CONSUMPTION ESTIMATE (Class I-IX)\n- **Class I:** 382,800 lbs over 30 days (\u00b17%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n- **Class II:** 79,200 lbs over 30 days (\u00b110%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n- **Class III:** 462,000 gal over 30 days (\u00b122%); primary pre-positioning source: **Blount Island Command**.\n- **Class IV:** 198,000 lbs over 30 days (\u00b120%); primary pre-positioning source: **Blount Island Command**.\n- **Class V:** 1,452,000 lbs over 30 days (\u00b130%); primary pre-positioning source: **Blount Island Command**.\n- **Class VI:** 33,000 lbs over 30 days (\u00b18%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n- **Class VII:** 726 ea over 30 days (\u00b130%); primary pre-positioning source: **Blount Island Command**.\n- **Class VIII:** 92,400 lbs over 30 days (\u00b114%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n- **Class IX:** 316,800 lbs over 30 days (\u00b118%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n\n## PARA 4 \u2014 RISKS & CONTINGENCY\n- **Class V ammunition** is the principal risk: required quantity exceeds listed primary-source on-hand levels, with **\u00b130%** variance. Contingency: phase loads forward early, cross-level from adjacent stocks, and trigger follow-on issue from alternate ammunition holding activities.\n- **Class III POL** demand is high and primary-source inventory is near total requirement, with **\u00b122%** variance. Contingency: establish distributed fuel nodes, enforce consumption discipline, and plan supplemental bulk fuel delivery from alternate maritime or theater distribution points.\n- **Class IX repair parts** remain a readiness driver; requirement nearly matches primary-source on-hand with **\u00b118%** variance. Contingency: prioritize high-failure assemblies, push bench stock forward, and use expedited redistribution from secondary maintenance depots.\n- **Class VII major end items** present replacement risk due to **\u00b130%** variance and limited on-hand depth at the primary source. Contingency: maintain controlled float, cannibalize non-mission-essential assets when directed, and request theater-level substitution where feasible.\n- **Class VIII medical supplies** may surge above forecast in tropical and high-opscale conditions. Contingency: pre-stage trauma/resuscitative sets and coordinate emergency replenishment through medical logistics channels.\n\n## PARA 5 \u2014 SOURCES & SIGNAL\nOriginator: **TRACE / LOGCOM sustainment cell**. Source data derived from provided 30-day consumption estimate and stated primary depot holdings at **MCLB Albany** and **Blount Island Command**. Next refresh: **281200Z APR 2026** or upon significant change to personnel, opscale, or mission profile.  \n**Classification: UNCLASSIFIED // FOR OFFICIAL USE**",
    "source": "hero"
  },
