    "brief": "**Sustainment Estimate Brief \u2014 RCT 15-Day LOGCOM Support Outlook (DTG 272025Z APR 2026)**\n\n## PARA 1 \u2014 SITUATION\nSupported force is a **Regimental Combat Team (RCT)** of **4,800** personnel over **15 days** in a **temperate** climate at **medium** opscale. Current estimate is based on steady-state sustainment demand across Classes I-IX for the stated window, with primary support split between MCLB Albany and Blount Island Command.\n\n## PARA 2 \u2014 MISSION\nLOGCOM sustainment cell provides forecast-based sourcing, staging, and distribution planning to maintain uninterrupted support to the RCT throughout the 15-day window. Priority is to pre-position high-demand and high-variance commodities forward enough to absorb operational fluctuation while preserving depot responsiveness.\n\n## PARA 3 \u2014 CONSUMPTION ESTIMATE (Class I-IX)\n- **Class I:** 345,600 lbs over 15 days (\u00b15%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n- **Class II:** 43,200 lbs over 15 days (\u00b18%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n- **Class III:** 230,400 gal over 15 days (\u00b112%); primary pre-positioning source: **Blount Island Command**.\n- **Class IV:** 115,200 lbs over 15 days (\u00b115%); primary pre-positioning source: **Blount Island Command**.\n- **Class V:** 576,000 lbs over 15 days (\u00b120%); primary pre-positioning source: **Blount Island Command**.\n- **Class VI:** 28,800 lbs over 15 days (\u00b16%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n- **Class VII:** 24 ea over 15 days (\u00b125%); primary pre-positioning source: **Blount Island Command**.\n- **Class VIII:** 43,200 lbs over 15 days (\u00b110%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n- **Class IX:** 172,800 lbs over 15 days (\u00b112%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n\n## PARA 4 \u2014 RISKS & CONTINGENCY\n- **Class V ammunition** carries the highest forecasted bulk demand and significant variance (\u00b120%); recommend forward buffering from **Blount Island Command** and phased push packages to avoid surge shortfalls.\n- **Class III POL** remains operationally decisive; consumption may rise with maneuver tempo, idle time, and generator load. Contingency is accelerated replenishment from **Blount Island Command** with prioritized line-haul and temporary stockage increase.\n- **Class IX repair parts** risk is tied to maintenance spikes and battle damage; establish demand-based reorder triggers and cross-level from **MCLB Albany** reserve stocks as readiness indicators shift.\n- **Class VII major end items** shows the highest variance percentage (\u00b125%) despite low quantity; hold replacement float at **Blount Island Command** and prepare rapid issue for mission-essential losses.\n- **Class IV barrier/construction materials** may increase if survivability or route-hardening requirements expand; contingency sourcing remains **Blount Island Command** with controlled release by priority of work.\n\n## PARA 5 \u2014 SOURCES & SIGNAL\nOriginator: **TRACE / LOGCOM sustainment cell**.  \nPrimary source nodes referenced: **MCLB Albany** and **Blount Island Command**.  \nNext refresh time: **281200Z APR 2026**.  \nClassification: UNCLASSIFIED // FOR OFFICIAL USE",
