    "brief": "**Sustainment Estimate Brief \u2014 DTG 272026Z APR 2026**\n\n## PARA 1 \u2014 SITUATION\nSupported force is a **MAGTF (reinforced)** of **7,500** personnel operating over **60 days** in **arid** climate at **high** opscale. Sustainment planning basis reflects sustained high-tempo operations in an arid environment, with demand weighted toward fuel, ammunition, repair parts, subsistence, and medical support across the full window.\n\n## PARA 2 \u2014 MISSION\nLOGCOM sustainment cell estimates, stages, and coordinates Class I-IX support required to maintain the force through the 60-day operational window. Priority is to pre-position high-demand commodities forward from designated depots and preserve continuity of support under variable consumption conditions.\n\n## PARA 3 \u2014 CONSUMPTION ESTIMATE (Class I-IX)\n- **Class I:** 2,430,000 lbs over 60 days (\u00b16%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n- **Class II:** 360,000 lbs over 60 days (\u00b19%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n- **Class III:** 2,880,000 gal over 60 days (\u00b118%); primary pre-positioning source: **Blount Island Command**.\n- **Class IV:** 990,000 lbs over 60 days (\u00b118%); primary pre-positioning source: **Blount Island Command**.\n- **Class V:** 8,550,000 lbs over 60 days (\u00b128%); primary pre-positioning source: **Blount Island Command**.\n- **Class VI:** 225,000 lbs over 60 days (\u00b16%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n- **Class VII:** 45,000 ea over 60 days (\u00b128%); primary pre-positioning source: **Blount Island Command**.\n- **Class VIII:** 495,000 lbs over 60 days (\u00b112%); primary pre-positioning source: **MCLB Albany**.\n- **Class IX:** 1,890,000 lbs over 60 days (\u00b115%); primary pre-positioning source: **Blount Island Command**.\n\n## PARA 4 \u2014 RISKS & CONTINGENCY\n- **Class V ammunition** carries the highest variance (\u00b128%) and largest total tonnage; contingency is phased push packages, tighter expenditure reporting, and surge sourcing through **Blount Island Command** with follow-on redistribution from theater stocks if available.\n- **Class III POL** demand remains highly sensitive to maneuver tempo and arid operating conditions (\u00b118%); contingency is to establish forward bulk storage, enforce fuel discipline, and schedule replenishment cycles from **Blount Island Command** with alternate commercial line-haul or host-nation bulk support if authorized.\n- **Class IX repair parts** risk is driven by high usage rates, dust-related wear, and maintenance backlog (\u00b115%); contingency is to pre-build high-failure bench stock, prioritize deadlining parts, and pull emergency resupply from **Blount Island Command** backed by expedited distribution channels.\n- **Class VII major end items** shows high variance (\u00b128%) with limited on-hand depth at source; contingency is controlled issue, battle-damage assessment for repair-versus-replace decisions, and cross-leveling from adjacent supported inventories before depot replenishment.\n- **Class IV barrier/construction material** may spike with survivability or route-hardening requirements (\u00b118%); contingency is early demand validation and supplemental sourcing from **Blount Island Command** plus local procurement where approved.\n\n## PARA 5 \u2014 SOURCES & SIGNAL\nOriginator: **TRACE / LOGCOM sustainment cell**.  \nPrimary sources referenced: **MCLB Albany** and **Blount Island Command**.  \nNext refresh: **282026Z APR 2026**.  \nClassification: UNCLASSIFIED // FOR OFFICIAL USE",
